# Zoc AI — 5-Year Implementation Prompts

> Companion to `doc/5years.me`.
> One **ready-to-paste prompt** per year. Each one is a year-long brief for a team (or an AI agent operating over months). They are intentionally higher-level than `6pro.me` — strategy + scope + non-negotiables, not file-level deliverables. Convert each one into a quarterly OKR set when the year starts.
>
> **How to use.** At the start of each year: read the prompt → break into 4 quarters → break each quarter into ~6 monthly briefs (like `6pro.me`) → break each month into shippable PR-sized tasks.

---

## PROMPT — YEAR 1: Product–Market Fit

**Context.**
v3.0.0 just launched (end of `6pro.me`). The app has signed installers, auto-update, a polished onboarding, persistent permissions, MCP support, and a marketing site.

**Mission.**
Prove that Zoc AI is something a non-trivial number of developers want to use every day. Get to 50k MAU, 30% week-2 retention, NPS ≥ 40.

**Strategic priorities.**
1. **Listen relentlessly.** Weekly user interviews (≥ 5/week). In-app feedback widget. Discord office hours. Public roadmap voting.
2. **Ship fast and small.** Two-week release cadence. Every release notes-worthy.
3. **Lighthouse users.** Land 3–5 well-known OSS maintainers as daily users. Pay for their time if needed. Their tweets are your top growth channel.
4. **Opt-in telemetry.** What tools/models/workflows are people actually using? Feed it back into prioritization.
5. **Performance never regresses.** Add a perf-budget CI check (cold-boot, indexing throughput, p95 streaming latency) that fails PRs that regress > 10%.
6. **Plugin API v0.** Even if rough — third parties need a way to extend the app or the ecosystem can't start.
7. **MCP everywhere.** Zoc AI becomes both an MCP client (uses external MCP tools) AND server (exposes its own tools to other clients). Land this early.

**Non-negotiables.**
- Local-first. Cloud features are always opt-in; air-gapped use must keep working.
- No proprietary lock-in for users' data. Sessions, transcripts, prompts are exportable formats.
- The core stays MIT/Apache licensed.

**Year-end exit criteria.**
- 50k MAU.
- ≥ 30% week-2 retention.
- NPS ≥ 40.
- Sub-second cold-open on a 100k-LOC repo.
- Plugin API v0 documented + at least 10 third-party plugins published.
- Clear top-3 list of features users would pay for (this seeds Year 2 + 3 monetization).

**Out of scope.**
- Hosted SaaS.
- Mobile.
- Enterprise sales motion.

**Hand-off to Year 2.**
End-of-year doc: "Top 10 things we learned, top 5 things to double down on, top 3 things to kill."

